On February 12, 2020, Wuhan had an estimated 3,509 unquarantined infected cases, which decreased to 334 by February 21, 2020. Based on data up to February 21, our model predicts that COVID-19 will likely end in Wuhan and Hunan by late March, mid March for the rest of China, and before early March for the four tier-one cities. In total, it is estimated that 80,511 individuals are infected in China, with 49,510 in Wuhan, 17,679 in Hunan (excluding Wuhan), and 13,322 in other regions of China.

Recommendations include maintaining strict quarantine and control measures until the specified timeframes in Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, and Shenzhen, and until late March in Hunan. The model can also be applied to predict epidemic trends and provide guidance for at-risk countries like South Korea, Japan, Italy, and Iran. This study highlights the unique characteristics and challenges posed by COVID-19, emphasizing the need for proactive intervention strategies.
